definition: "Folate is the natural form of vitamin B9 found in food; folic acid is the synthetic oxidized form used in supplements and food fortification. In the body, both must be converted to the active form 5-methyltetrahydrofolate (5-MTHF) before they can participate in biological reactions. Folate functions as a methyl group donor in one-carbon metabolism — a central biochemical pathway that drives DNA methylation (which regulates gene expression), DNA synthesis and repair, and the conversion of homocysteine to methionine. Folate works in close collaboration with vitamin B12 in these reactions; deficiency of either produces similar downstream effects including elevated homocysteine and impaired DNA metabolism."
why_it_matters: "Folate status has implications that span the full arc of longevity: from cancer prevention (via DNA methylation and repair) to cardiovascular risk (via homocysteine metabolism) to cognitive function and dementia prevention. Overt folate deficiency — producing megaloblastic anemia — has largely been eliminated in countries with mandatory food fortification, but suboptimal folate status that impairs DNA methylation and elevates homocysteine remains common. Approximately 15–20% of adults have the MTHFR C677T genetic variant that impairs folic acid conversion efficiency, increasing their requirement for the pre-converted form (5-MTHF). Because both deficiency and the MTHFR variant are common, and because the consequences of suboptimal folate are serious and underappreciated, testing folate status is a meaningful part of any longevity evaluation."

